IFPREVERB LAUGH -1
        CLEARVERB
        AFFECT 2759
        ECHO ALL You hear %n laughing uproariously.
        AFFECT 2303
        ECHO PLAYER You laugh uproariously, the sound echoing in all directions.
        ECHO OTHERS %N laughs uproariously, the sound echoing in all directions.
        AFFECT 2301
        ECHO ALL You hear %n laughing uproariously.
        AFFECT 2302
        ECHO ALL You hear %n laughing uproariously.
        AFFECT 2304
        ECHO ALL You hear %n laughing uproariously.
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START
You're certain that the shaft ends just below you, out of sight in the
darkness but not a great distance now. The top of the glass-walled shaft
is nothing but a point of reddish light far above.
*DESCRIPTION_END

;
;

NUMBER 2304
NAME Glassine cave
DEEPCAVE
DARKNESS
EXIT ABOVE 2303

IFENTRY
        IFVAR INTNUM60 = 444
                EQUAL INTNUM60 0
                POSITION STAND
                DAMAGEPLR CRUSH 200 You smash into the floor of the cavern.
                POSITION KNEEL
                DAMAGEPLR CRUSH 100 You bounce off the floor and hit one wall.
                POSITION SIT
                DAMAGEPLR CRUSH 50 You ricochet from the wall to the floor again.
                POSITION LAY
                DAMAGEPLR CRUSH 25 Finally, you keel over and smash against the floor one last time.
        ENDIF
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START
This cave is shaped like an open-topped cone, its walls forming a circular
triangle overhead. The floor and the walls themselves are of the same
glassine substance which makes up the shaft overhead, a very smooth and
very, very hard substance. A tunnel has been made in the northmost part
of the wall, irregular and unusual in appearance.
*DESCRIPTION_END

ITEM 0 77 ADJ1=396 VAL2=2305

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 0
The tunnel seems to have been melted through the glassine wall and the
volcanic rock beyond it, but in a much more casual, sloppy way than the shaft
itself. Its walls are malformed and drooped under their own, soft weight when
freshly heated, then froze into a contorted, rather ugly appearance.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB DIG -1
        CLEARVERB
        IFVAR LEV < 31
                ECHO PLAYER There's nowhere to dig.
        ENDIF
        IFVAR LEV > 20
                ECHO PLAYER Some inner instinct restrains you from digging in every location on every outing. Possibly an image of nuclear fire rushing through your hands and incinerating you, or maybe just someone stabbing you with a pointed stick.
                GMMSG %N has received the nuclear-fire and pointed-stick dig warning message.
        ENDIF
ENDIF

ITEM 1 420 ADJ1=693 ADJ2=143

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 1
The walls are, indeed, round, glassine and very smooth. You could never
climb them, not in a million years...
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB CLIMB 1
        CLEARVERB
        IFVAR FLAG2 ! 22
                ECHO PLAYER You try to climb the wall, but it is far too smooth.
                ECHO OTHERS %N does a funny dance against one part of the wall.
        ENDIF
        IFVAR FLAG2 = 22
                ECHO PLAYER ...but you just had to try it, didn't you? Well, even licking your hands and using them as suction cups doesn't work. Satisfied?
                ECHO OTHERS %N seems to be trying to adhere to the glassine walls by licking %h hands and using them as suction cups.
                GMMSG %N looked at the wall in room 2304, then tried to climb anyway. %S is therefore being taunted by the script, with a MWTB reference.
        ENDIF
ENDIF


IFPREVERB LOOK 1
        EQUAL FLAG2 22
ENDIF

IFVERB RECALL -1
        CLEARVERB
        ECHO PLAYER You have no stunning realizations.
ENDIF

;
;

NUMBER 2305
NAME Meltwall chamber
DEEPCAVE

EXIT ABOVE 2306

*DESCRIPTION_START
The walls of this chamber have been heated to the melting point several
times in the past, then allowed to cool as they deformed and flowed like
softened wax. As a result, there are no level surfaces on the floor nor
smooth places on any wall. The actual texture of the surroundings is the
same glassine substance you have seen elsewhere, but its exposure to heat
has made it easier to grasp and get a grip on, which is fortunate, as you
would never be able to make your way around the formations the dripping
stuff has formed otherwise.
*DESCRIPTION_END

DARKNESS

ITEM 0 77 ADJ1=396 VAL2=2304
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 0
The tunnel is a misshapen mess, as heat-warped as the walls of the chamber.
*DESCRIPTION_END

ITEM 1 1271 ADJ1=92 ADJ2=143
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 1
The formation is a misshapen lump of glass with projections, rounded like
pseudopodae, hanging from its sides and lolling, frozen forever, atop it.
Created through the action of dripping, molten stone and glass, it reminds
you of a squat, enormous toad or demonic being of some kind.
*DESCRIPTION_END

ITEM 2 420 ADJ1=131 VAL2=2306
EXTEND 2 of glassine stone
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 2
While the stone and glass have actually stopped flowing, and are likely to
remain in place as they are for a long, long time, the appearance of fluid
motion is caused by the interplay of light and shadow over the strangely
shaped projections and pieces of wall. At the base, where wall becomes
floor, the projections are quite small and smooth, while higher up they
grow quite a bit more irregular.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB CLIMB 2
        CLEARVERB
        DISBAND
        IFVAR FLAG3 ! 33
                SKILLCHECK 5 -50 DUMMY1
                IFVAR DUMMY1 < 0
                        ECHO PLAYER You can't seem to find a good place to start this low on the wall. %c[Round: 10 sec]
                        ECHO OTHERS %N tries to climb the lower reaches of the wall, but can't seem to do it.
                ENDIF
                IFVAR DUMMY1 >= 0
                        ECHO PLAYER You apply your climbing skills, scrambling up to the easy part, then clambering onwards.
                        ECHO OTHERS %N scrambles up the lowest part of the wall, the climbs out of sight.
                        MOVE 2306
                        AFFECT 2306
                        ECHO OTHERS %N climbs up from below.
                        ECHO PLAYER [Round: 10 sec]
                        EQUAL ROUNDTIME 10
                        POSITION KNEEL
                ENDIF
        ENDIF
        IFVAR FLAG3 = 33
                SKILLCHECK 5 50 DUMMY1
                IFVAR DUMMY1 < 0
                        ECHO PLAYER You think you can do it, though, despite this failure. %c[Round: 5 sec]
                        ECHO OTHERS %N tries to climb the easy part of the chamber wall.
                        EQUAL ROUNDTIME 5
                ENDIF
                IFVAR DUMMY1 >= 0
                        ECHO PLAYER You climb the easy part of the wall from the top of the formation.
                        ECHO OTHERS %N climbs from the top of the formation up the easy part of the wall and out of sight.
                        MOVE 2306
                        AFFECT 2306
                        ECHO OTHERS %N climbs up from below.
                        ECHO PLAYER [Round: 10 sec]
                        EQUAL ROUNDTIME 10
                        POSITION KNEEL
                ENDIF
        ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB CLIMB 1
        CLEARVERB
        ECHO PLAYER You clamber up on top of the stone formation.
        ECHO OTHERS %N clambers up onto %a.
        POSITION KNEEL
        EQUAL FLAG3 33
ENDIF

